      • setInitialValueDateAndTime

        public void setInitialValueDateAndTime(java.lang.String dateAndTimeFormat,
                              int dateAndTimeDayOffset,
                              java.lang.String dateAndTimeTimeZone)
        Set the date and time for the initial value. The type of the initial value is implicitly set to INITIAL_VALUE_TYPE_DATE_AND_TIME.
        Parameters:
        dateAndTimeFormat - the date and time format. Example: "yyyy-MM-dd." The following placeholders are supported for the date and time format:
        Letter Date or Time Component Presentation Examples
        G Era designator Text AD
        y Year Year 1996; 96
        M Month in year Month July; Jul; 07
        w Week in year Number 27
        W Week in month Number 2
        D Day in year Number 189
        d Day in month Number 10
        F Day of week in month Number 2
        E Day in week Text Tuesday; Tue
        a Am/pm marker Text PM
        H Hour in day (0-23) Number 0
        k Hour in day (1-24) Number 24
        K Hour in am/pm (0-11) Number 0
        h Hour in am/pm (1-12) Number 12
        m Minute in hour Number 30
        s Second in minute Number 55
        S Millisecond Number 978
        dateAndTimeDayOffset - the offset in days: <0 = past, 0 = execution day, >0 = future
        dateAndTimeTimeZone - the time zone (String of 3 characters, see dfischer.utils.ZoneTime)
        See Also:
        INITIAL_VALUE_TYPE_DATE_AND_TIME, ZoneTime.timeZoneArray

      • isVarNameValid

        public static boolean isVarNameValid(java.lang.String varName)
        Check if all characters for a var name are valid. Valid characters for a var name are only '0'..'9', 'A'..'Z', 'a'..'z' and '_'. The first character must be a letter.
        Note that you have additionally to check the name also with isJavaKeyword(String varName).
        Parameters:
        varName - the name of the var to check.
        Returns:
        true if the name is valid.
        See Also:
        isJavaKeyword(String)

      • isJavaKeyword

        public static boolean isJavaKeyword(java.lang.String varName)
        Check if a (proposed) name for a var is a java keyword. In such a case the var name is invalid. Note that you have additionally to check the name also with isVarNameValid(String varName).
        Parameters:
        varName - the name of the var to check.
        Returns:
        true if the name for the var is a java keyword
        See Also:
        isVarNameValid(String)
